Foot and Mouth Disease in Argentina
Follow-up report No. 15
Translation of information received on 20 June 2001 from Dr Bernardo
Gabriel Cane, President, National Service for Agrifood Health and
Quality (SENASA), Secretariat for Agriculture, Livestock, Fisheries
and Food, Buenos Aires:
End of previous report period: 9 June 2001 (see Disease Information,
14 [24], 148, dated 15 June 2001).
End of this report period: 16 June 2001.
New outbreaks: during the week from 10 to 16 June 2001, a total of
103 outbreaks of foot and mouth disease were confirmed clinically and
by laboratory tests in cattle in various districts and departments in
provinces of Argentina.
Total number of outbreaks confirmed up to 16 June 2001: 1351.
Affected animals: the number of affected animals is 7604, [including?]
64 pigs and 6 sheep, out of 121 286 animals exposed to the risk of
infection. The category most affected is heifers.
Location of the outbreaks: 79 percent of the outbreaks occurred in
Buenos Aires province, 7 percent in Entre Rios province and 6 percent
in Santa Fe province.
Control measures: the main strategies are applied through vaccination
and movement control. Measures for transit control provided for in the
regulations in force are being implemented. The first vaccination round
against foot and mouth disease is due to be completed at the end of
June [2001].
Brazil
-------
[see also:
Foot & mouth disease - Brazil (Rio Grande do Sul) 20010510.0908
Foot & mouth disease - Brazil: OIE report 20010515.0941
Foot & mouth dis. - Brazil (Rio Grande do Sul) (06) 20010531.1076]
Date: 25 Jun 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE 19 Jun 2001 [edited]

PORTO ALEGRE, BRAZIL: On Tuesday, Brazilian health authorities
confirmed the discovery of a new source of foot and mouth disease
(FMD) in the southern state of Rio Grande do Sul, where 13 million
animals were vaccinated and another 1118 were killed after an earlier
outbreak last May [2001].
The appearance of the new outbreak coincided with a visit from a team
of scientists from the European Union sent to the region to ensure the
disease had been eradicated in order to resume beef imports from
southern Brazil.
The new outbreak, initially affecting 15 animals, surfaced on a ranch
located in the town of Rio Grande, some 300 kilometers (185 miles)
from Porto Alegre, near the border with Uruguay.
Until May 2001, Rio Grande do Sul, which borders Argentina and
Uruguay, was one of the 2 Brazilian states with international certificates
declaring the area free of FMD without having had to resort to
vaccination.
The region, which contains 8 percent of Brazil's cattle, was forced to
halt its beef exports in early May [2001] due to an outbreak of FMD,
and it has been attempting to resume beef sales by implementing the
vaccination program and the eradication of infected cattle.
Uruguay
